passages.text: Upward Revisions Set to Continue; Reiterate Overweight/Analyst Focus List; Key Mgmt Takes

PM's take: one of the best upward revision momentum stories in our coverage as the truth sets ULTA free. ULTA produced a very high quality beat (Figure 1) with comps well- ahead of our raised- into- the- print forecast and strong flow- through to the bottom- line (along with merchandise margin expansion). The company gained share for the second consecutive qtr as Sephora at KSS headwinds fade (Figure 9) while the category accelerated on the prestige side (+MSD from +LSD with mass holding at +LSD). Looking ahead, the company guided the top- line conservatively despite ongoing momentum in the business and no change in behavior from the consumer. On the bottom- line, the step up in SG&A growth is essentially incentive comp, the Space NK acquisition, and variable expenses given the upward sales revision as investment spending is essentially on track (though we continue to see conservatism on this line as well). Indeed, as we previewed, estimates continue to trend to the \(25 - 26\) baseline argued post 1Q with 2026 in the \(28 - 30\) , also as expected. Given \(4\% +\) comps coming back into play, ULTA's algo, share gains, and the quality of the industry along with ULTA's perch, we believe it should trade at a premium to a normalized market multiple of 18x. As such, our Dec 2026 price target of \(\) 600\(is based on 19x PE on our 2027 estimate. ULTA remains Overweight and one of our three US Equity Analyst Focus List stocks.

(1) Guidance raised for 2Q beat and a stronger (but prudent) 2H top-line outlook. ULTA raised its top- and bottom-line guide to \(\) 12.0-12.1\(B net sales on a +2.5 - 3.5\%\) comp and \(\) 23.85-24.30\(EPS vs.\) \ \(11.5 - 11.7\) B net sales, flat to \(+1.5\%\) comps, and \(\) 22.65-23.20\(EPS prior (with some of the sales lift and SG&A pressures due to the Space NK acquisition. See Figure 2 for full guidance details. Notably, the raise reflects 2Q outperformance as well as a stronger 2H outlook given more macro clarity vs. 1Q, with ULTA expecting flat to +LSD comps in 2H vs. the Street's \~1% per Consensus Metrix. While the company wouldn't comment on QTD in our follow-up, ULTA noted that there has been no change in consumer spending patterns or category engagement and their share performance remains strong. While trends likely slowed from July, ULTA shifted a major event with all three weeks in July this year vs. two last year (spawning late June to July 2024).

(2) ULTA continues to out-comp Sephora at KSS and maintains share gains; cosmetics inflects positive. 2Q comps of \(+6.7\%\) (vs. +LSD mass and +MSD prestige category growth with the latter accelerating from +LSD in 1Q) again well-exceeded Street expectations of \(+2.9\%\) and compared to \(-5\%\) buyside expectations, per our work, driven by traffic \(+3.7\%\) (vs. \(+0.6\%\) in 1Q) and ticket \(+2.9\%\) (vs. \(+2.3\%\) in 1Q). From a cadence perspective, growth was strongest in May and July due to timing shifts of key promo events. From a category perspective, all categories composed positive with fragrance continuing to lead and up robust +DD (successful Mother's/Father's Day activations, compelling newness, and strength in gift sets and men's fragrances), while

We rate ULTA Overweight as we see category growth returning to its longer term trend of \(3 - 4\%\) with the company benefitting from its unique mass/prestige combination and industry perch, both leading to share gains. This should result in improved margin flow- through and earnings growth and multiple expansion. ULTA sits in a unique position where it knows more about its consumers than the brands given its loyalty program. It is also the only national beauty retailer to offer prestige and mass products as well as services and a market- leading hair care assortment across brands. Lastly, department stores are long- term share donors.

Our Dec 2026 price target of \(600 is based on 19x PE on our 2027 estimate. Given \(4\% +\) comps coming back into play, ULTA's algo, share gains, and the quality of the industry along with ULTA's perch, we believe it should trade at a premium to a normalized market multiple of 18x.

skincare and wellness were +HSD (led body care and wellness with mass/prestige skincare +LSD), makeup was +MSD (the first positive cosmetic company since 2Q23) in part from lapping the Ulta Beauty Collection reset (mass +HSD and prestige +LSD), haircare was +MSD (led by professional hairdresser, accessories, and hair tools), and services was +LSD (led by cut & color). This compares to Sephora at Kohl's competing flat over the same period (vs. +1% last quarter). Indeed, ULTA returned to share gains in 10 and this persisted in 2Q (both mass and prestige) as the headwind from KSS's aggressive rollout of Sephora's shop- in- shops is moderating, and we expect continued progress in 2025 (Figure 9). Notably, ULTA launched 24 new brands in the qtr (43 new brands YTD vs. 30 LY) and spoke to a strong newness pipeline for the remainder of the year. On the consumer, ULTA consumers remain resilient and have been increasingly focused on events, value, and promotions over the past year.

(3) Gross margin well-ahead of expectations; merch margin up on tighter promotional stance. 2Q gross margin was +90 bps YOY vs. the Street's flat estimate, driven first by lower shrink (est 45 bps) and then higher merch margins (est 20 bps), partially offset by supply chain deleverage (wages and optimization costs) and other revenue (dollars flat YOY). The merch margin improvement was driven by eliminating unproductive and overlapping promotions to improve clarity (Figure 10, a particularly easy lap including clearance from their private brand relaunch a year ago), the ERP disruption from 2Q24, and implementing new functionality such as Replenish & Save to drive greater engagement (a moat against AMZN, in our view). Looking ahead, mgmt continues to expect gross margin contraction for the year on store occupancy and supply chain costs, partially offset by lower shrink with merch margins expected to be flatish. On 2H specifically, the company expects shrink benefits will start to moderate (particularly in 4Q on a tough compare), fixed cost deleverage, and ULTA is also lapping lower e-comm shipping rate benefits in the back half. We are modeling FY25 GM of 39.0% (+20 bps YOY) vs. the Street's 38.5% into the print.

(4) SG&A/Investments; 2025 still an investment year. 2Q SG&A dollars increased \(\) 97\mathrm{MM}\$ YOY (+15%; inclusive of \(\) 7\mathrm{MM}\$ one-time costs related to the Space NK acquisition) with SG&A as a % of sales deleveraging 130 bps on higher incentive comp (est 20 bps), store payroll/benefits (est 84 bps), and corporate overhead (est 53 bps). More specifically, the incentive comp deleverage was driven by stronger 2Q performance and lapping IC favorability last year, the store payroll increase reflected higher healthcare costs and more selling hours, and higher overhead due to investments to support the ULTA Beauty Unleashed strategy. Additionally, advertising was roughly neutral in the qtr. Looking ahead, mgmt expects SG&A growth to be elevated in 2H given the shift of investment spending from 1H, the inclusion of Space NK expenses and lapping reduced planned spend last year (SG&A +1% in 2H24 vs. 8% in 1H24). Overall, FY25 SG&A growth is now expected to be +13-14% vs. +10% prior. Notably, the investment spend and marketing investments are trending materially in-line with ULTA's plan with the higher growth rate a function of the inclusion of Space NK, incentive comp, and variable expenses given the raised top-line outlook. We are now modeling FY25 SG&A dollars of \(\) 3,206\mathrm{MM}\$ , representing YOY growth of \(\sim 14\%\) .

(5) TGT headwind lower than estimated on flow-through rate. Recall, ULTA initially indicated at our April conference its plans to halt its long-term 800 shop-in-shop expansion to the current \(\sim 610\) doors. Shortly thereafter, Retail Brew showcased a TGT employee Reddit thread from 3/20/2025 that revealed (i) severe theft issues within the shop-in-shops (with one employee loosely citing \(>10\mathrm{K}\) /month) and (ii) labor issues as designated Ulta staffing agreements were ignored. The company formally announced earlier this month that it would end the partnership in August 2026. In assessing the potential headwind to operating profit, we note that TGT indicated on its 2Q call that their core beauty assortment comprises \(\sim 95\%\) of total beauty sales, implying \(\sim 5\%\) for ULTA. ULTA's commentary was that FY24 TGT royalties were \(

\(\) 113\mathrm{MM}\(corroborating our previously noted\) \ \(65\mathrm{MM}\) estimate. That said, the company indicated a \(60 - 65\%\) flow- through given operating costs, which reduces the headwind to a much more manageable \(\sim\) 40MM/30 bps to op margin split between FY26 and FY27. Looking ahead, mgmt expects the TGT partnership profit pool will ultimately be more than offset in other revenue by several initiatives including UB Media, marketplace, and franchise royalties from the Middle East expansion.
- Please also see our initial thoughts on ULTA's decision to part ways with its prior CFO.
